name: ethylene cyanohydrin
Reason: The basic units to consider for ethylene cyanohydrin (N#CCCO) are acetonitrile (CH3CN) and ethylene glycol (HOCH2CH2OH). Acetonitrile has a melting point of -45.7°C, which provides a starting point. The hydroxyl group typically raises the melting point due to hydrogen bonding. The effect of a hydroxyl group is substantial and could raise the melting point by up to +50°C compared to molecules without hydrogen bonding capability. However, since we are adding this to an already polar molecule with a cyano group, the overall effect might be less pronounced. Therefore, the hydroxyl group might add only around +20 to +30°C to the melting point of the molecule. Furthermore, the ethylene linker (two carbon chain) present in ethylene glycol is flexible and reduces the overall melting point but to a lesser extent, possibly in the range of -5 to -10°C. Combining these effects, the predicted melting point would be slightly higher than that of acetonitrile but lowered due to the ethylene linker.
